00:18:34,201 --> 00:18:39,902
And then the other side of it is we've started doing one-on-one lessons in the darkroom.

265
00:18:40,583 --> 00:18:47,824
I work directly with somebody who maybe has printed a little bit in the darkroom or maybe never has, but they're interested in it.

266
00:18:48,544 --> 00:18:54,746
And I sort of work with them to make a really beautiful print of one of their photographs.

267
00:18:55,246 --> 00:18:58,987
And I show them how to make certain decisions about how to make it look the way you want.

268
00:18:59,427 --> 00:19:08,910
whether it's altering the contrast or adding or subtracting time to your exposure, and then, you know, how to process it properly so that it's going to be archival.

269
00:19:09,190 --> 00:19:12,051
And that's been very satisfying for me and I think for the people who have done it.

270
00:19:12,211 --> 00:19:12,811
I'm sure it is.

271
00:19:12,851 --> 00:19:14,532
So you actually do one-on-one.

272
00:19:14,572 --> 00:19:18,293
