It was, you know, plywood on the toilet.

284
00:19:48,363 --> 00:19:57,909
But it worked, you know, and fortunately the houses we had were always one and a half bathrooms, so no emergencies messed up what we were doing.

285
00:19:57,929 --> 00:19:58,690
I would hope not, yeah.

286
00:19:58,710 --> 00:19:59,631
But it was like magic.

287
00:19:59,731 --> 00:20:06,836
You know, you put this piece of paper after you expose it to what was like a slide projector, and all of a sudden it came up.

288
00:20:07,476 --> 00:20:10,638
And it's still like, it's still really exciting.

289
00:20:11,278 --> 00:20:29,247
And so to introduce people to it, particularly when they've gone from digital, where it's just, you know, a bigger version of your printer, to actually seeing, and Ross sort of, you know, the changes that you can make with your hands and with, are so subtle, and it's kind of like, you know, tuning a guitar.

290
00:20:29,648 --> 00:20:31,148
At one point, it's beautiful.

291
00:20:31,829 --> 00:20:33,230
Before it, it's cacophonous.

