00:23:18,234 --> 00:23:19,455
It's absolute magic.

335
00:23:19,595 --> 00:23:20,375
It's so cool.

336
00:23:20,755 --> 00:23:24,678
I actually found some ancient stuff from 30 years ago and I gave it to her.

337
00:23:24,698 --> 00:23:25,499
We're gonna process it.

338
00:23:25,559 --> 00:23:26,400
Yeah, I gave it to her.

339
00:23:26,440 --> 00:23:27,360
I don't know what's on it.

340
00:23:27,400 --> 00:23:28,221
I have no idea.

341
00:23:28,261 --> 00:23:30,883
I hope it doesn't get me in any trouble.

342
00:23:30,903 --> 00:23:32,624
You never know.

343
00:23:32,704 --> 00:23:37,287
Years ago, before I went off to college, I worked at a camera store in Washington, D.C.

344
00:23:38,208 --> 00:23:40,209
and we had this elderly woman come in.

345
00:23:41,210 --> 00:23:47,634
And she had a roll of film that she discovered from 616 film, from a camera that hadn't been made for 50 years.

346
00:23:48,615 --> 00:23:51,117
And she said, I don't know if it's any good.

347
00:23:51,137 --> 00:23:53,759
And I said, well, it's a dollar to process the film.

348
00:23:54,279 --> 00:24:00,643
And she clearly was well-dressed and wealthy, and she lived in a house in downtown Washington, DC.

349
00:24:01,124 --> 00:24:02,645
I don't want to waste the money.

350
00:24:02,985 --> 00:24:05,927
And I said, well, you know, I'll throw it in when I develop my own film.

351
00:24:06,307 --> 00:24:07,388
I don't want to accept charity.

352
00:24:07,928 --> 00:24:10,989
So she came in once a day for two weeks asking.

353
00:24:11,449 --> 00:24:13,169
And finally I said, well, where did you store it?

354
00:24:13,769 --> 00:24:14,850
And she said, in the attic.

355
00:24:15,790 --> 00:24:17,250
I said, is the attic air conditioned?

356
00:24:17,350 --> 00:24:18,050
She said, no.

357
00:24:18,130 --> 00:24:19,811
So attic in Washington, D.C.

358
00:24:19,831 --> 00:24:22,751
in the summer is 140 degrees and it's cooked.

359
00:24:22,851 --> 00:24:25,692
So finally I said, you know, I can make sure.

360
00:24:25,712 --> 00:24:27,573
And she said, how would you do that?

361
00:24:27,613 --> 00:24:28,593
I said, let me look at the film.

362
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:29,393
And I opened up the film.

363
00:24:30,807 --> 00:24:32,067
And I said, nothing on it.

364
00:24:32,228 --> 00:24:32,828
It's no good.

365
00:24:33,208 --> 00:24:34,488
She thanked me so much.

366
00:24:34,968 --> 00:24:35,888
She could sleep better.

367
00:24:36,068 --> 00:24:37,649
And we threw the film away for her.

368
00:24:38,409 --> 00:24:42,530
But, you know, there's the process is weird.

369
00:24:42,930 --> 00:24:44,010
It's magic.

370
00:24:45,071 --> 00:24:49,452
I mean, I have similar those what I gave him is a roll of film.

371
00:24:49,492 --> 00:24:50,012
It's been in the

372
00:24:52,122 --> 00:24:55,225
I'm pretty sure it's you, because it's been in the container for 30 years now.

373
00:24:56,166 --> 00:24:58,868
Fortunately, it was never in an attic or, you know.

374
00:24:58,888 --> 00:25:03,772
Well, when we print it for National, that's a centennial exhibit for National Geographic.

375
00:25:04,272 --> 00:25:06,294
And the next time you come by, I'll show you the book we did.

376
00:25:06,414 --> 00:25:07,935
Yeah, I'm definitely going to.

377
00:25:08,236 --> 00:25:10,597
Once he gives me a call, tells me I'm all set, I'll be in.

378
00:25:11,359 --> 00:25:17,041
Well, they had film with negatives that were 100 years old that were anonymous that we made prints from.

379
00:25:18,442 --> 00:25:25,445
Part of the problem is that there was a period of time in the 30s when they made film using acetate and nitrate.

380
00:25:25,705 --> 00:25:29,306
And it's why there's no Hollywood films from the silent era, because they self-immolated.

381
00:25:29,346 --> 00:25:30,187
They would explode.

382
00:25:30,307 --> 00:25:32,127
Right, I remember that, the acetate.

383
00:25:32,147 --> 00:25:33,068
So, Geographic.

384
00:25:33,908 --> 00:25:44,331
Actually, the New York Times in 1946 threw away one and a half million negatives of prints that they had published in the previous 50 years of the Times.

385
00:25:45,151 --> 00:25:51,472
And if the photography editor knew you, you know, hey Joe Blow, we got 20 contact sheets of your film.

386
00:25:51,492 --> 00:25:52,753
Do you want it or should we toss it?

387
00:25:53,193 --> 00:25:54,133
Most of them said toss it.

388
00:25:55,484 --> 00:26:05,041
And so when we ended up working for the National Geographic, we ended up making copy negatives, really high quality, very expensive, so we could reproduce those images.

389
00:26:06,556 --> 00:26:09,517
You know, it's funny, I have, I think they called it Kodachrome.

390
00:26:09,857 --> 00:26:11,157
Oh, that was the best color.

391
00:26:11,917 --> 00:26:13,858
Still in the box, never been used.

392
00:26:14,258 --> 00:26:15,818
I have a few of them.

393
00:26:15,838 --> 00:26:28,881
My father was big into, you know, taking pictures, photography, whatever, and I ended up with a bunch of, I don't even know where it came from, but it's all unused, original box, it's never opened.

394
00:26:29,001 --> 00:26:31,362
That's wonderful, but you can't process Kodachrome anymore.

395
00:26:31,442 --> 00:26:31,882
No more.

396
00:26:32,502 --> 00:26:33,963
It was a chemical process.

397
00:26:34,083 --> 00:26:34,883
Yeah, I figured.

398
00:26:36,143 --> 00:26:40,885
It read the chemistry and it changed it each time and there was two labs in the world that did it.

399
00:26:41,786 --> 00:26:44,687
And Kodak shot them both down.

400
00:26:45,248 --> 00:26:51,131
My wife's going to be afraid now because she's going to hear what you said and she's going to think there's something on there that's going to explode in my car or something.

401
00:26:51,171 --> 00:26:54,372
No, that has to be a film that was made in the early 30s.

402
00:26:54,532 --> 00:26:55,373
Okay, well that's good.

403
00:26:55,553 --> 00:26:57,794
I hope this isn't the early 30s.

404
00:26:57,874 --> 00:27:00,395
You can tell when it goes bad because it smells like vinegar.

405
00:27:00,435 --> 00:27:01,756
I don't know, it's hard.

406
00:27:04,497 --> 00:27:07,059
Maybe when I come pick up the other stuff, I'll show you this.

407
00:27:07,099 --> 00:27:08,080
You can take a look at it.

408
00:27:08,100 --> 00:27:09,001
There's quite a bit of it.

