514
00:33:33,065 --> 00:33:38,285
I gotta ask you, alright, I know your worlds collided, whatever, but how did you guys meet?

515
00:33:39,178 --> 00:33:40,079
Let me take this one.

516
00:33:40,719 --> 00:33:48,323
When I was in school, Arlette's gallery, Gallery Kefes, was, as Gus mentioned, the best photography gallery in Boston.

517
00:33:49,284 --> 00:33:59,050
I went to openings there to see contemporary work and a friend of mine when I was at school became Arlette's assistant.

518
00:34:00,311 --> 00:34:03,292
I was envious because I wanted to be connected with that gallery.

519
00:34:05,438 --> 00:34:11,041
He eventually reached out to me because he said, hey, Arlette's husband needs some help with some framing jobs.

520
00:34:11,381 --> 00:34:13,262
And I had been working at a frame shop.

521
00:34:14,123 --> 00:34:16,104
I didn't know who Gus was at the time.

522
00:34:16,384 --> 00:34:19,926
And I said, sure, if it's at the gallery, I'm happy to get involved.

523
00:34:20,607 --> 00:34:26,630
I got there and immediately we left the gallery and went to the place in Chelsea, which I was like, where the hell is this guy taking me?

524
00:34:28,302 --> 00:34:31,106
When I get there, I recognize there's a massive darkroom in here.

525
00:34:31,146 --> 00:34:32,948
And I didn't have access to a darkroom at the time.

526
00:34:32,968 --> 00:34:35,992
I had finished school and I was looking for access to a darkroom.

527
00:34:36,172 --> 00:34:38,836
So I helped him with a couple of frame jobs.

528
00:34:39,136 --> 00:34:44,623
I was working for him maybe once a week and started trading access to the darkroom.

529
00:34:46,145 --> 00:34:49,167
You know, and then started working on some printing jobs for Gus.

530
00:34:49,828 --> 00:34:58,615
And, you know, it eventually became clear that we had a similar sensibility as to what looks great and, you know, how to do it and how to produce it efficiently.

531
00:34:59,898 --> 00:35:02,682
Now, you know, Gus is a well-known photographer.

532
00:35:02,702 --> 00:35:05,966
He has worked in many, many museums.

533
00:35:06,527 --> 00:35:11,674
It wasn't until after I started working for him that I really started to understand who he was.

534
00:35:11,794 --> 00:35:15,880
And occasionally we've started to work on some of Gus's

535
00:35:16,580 --> 00:35:17,321
That was always fun.

536
00:35:17,401 --> 00:35:22,564
Gus has a lifetime of photographs that have either not been printed or haven't been looked at in years.

537
00:35:22,644 --> 00:35:31,510
And part of the future of Palm Press, as I hope to take it over, is we'll be printing some- I'll be a client instead of- There you go.

538
00:35:31,550 --> 00:35:32,771
Printing some of Gus's work.

539
00:35:33,172 --> 00:35:34,913
So that's how it came to be.

540
00:35:35,013 --> 00:35:36,494
And yeah, we'll see.

541
00:35:36,574 --> 00:35:37,314
We'll see where it goes.

542
00:35:37,975 --> 00:35:44,759
One of the things I discovered that when you bring someone on board, usually there's a lot that they have to unlearn.

543
00:35:45,740 --> 00:35:47,141
bad habits.

544
00:35:47,701 --> 00:35:50,683
Ross, there was very, very little that Ross had to unlearn.

545
00:35:50,723 --> 00:35:52,143
And he is such an eager student.

546
00:35:52,904 --> 00:35:54,385
You know, is there a way we can do this?

547
00:35:54,445 --> 00:35:56,546
And I would remember some obscure chemist.

548
00:35:57,426 --> 00:35:59,547
And he would incorporate it into what he did.

549
00:35:59,607 --> 00:36:07,071
And he's come up with technical solutions for some of our clients' work, which you would think would be impossible.

550
00:36:07,192 --> 00:36:11,574
And they're brilliant, like the large digital negatives you made for the Iowa person.

551
00:36:12,755 --> 00:36:14,075
So one of the things that we've done is

552
00:36:15,636 --> 00:36:24,418
figured out a way to take a digital image, even sometimes iPhone images, and produce a negative by printing it on our inkjet printer.

553
00:36:24,718 --> 00:36:27,999
And then we use that negative to print it as a silver print in the darkroom.

554
00:36:28,139 --> 00:36:28,819
And they're beautiful.

555
00:36:28,879 --> 00:36:31,240
They're more beautiful than we thought they possibly could be.

